Here is a simple code fragment in Python to print out the multiplication table up to 10:
```
for i in range(1, 11):
    for j in range(1, 11):
        print(f"{i} x {j} = {i*j}")
    print()  # print a newline after each row
```
This code uses a nested loop to iterate over the numbers 1 to 10, and prints out the multiplication table for each pair of numbers. The `f` string notation is used to format the output string.

You can also use a similar code in other programming languages such as Java, C++, C#, etc.

Here is the equivalent code in Java:
```
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    for (int j = 1; j <= 10; j++) {
        System.out.printf("%d x %d = %d\n", i, j, i * j);
    }
    System.out.println();  // print a newline after each row
}
```
And here is the equivalent code in C++:
```
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    for (int j = 1; j <= 10; j++) {
        std::cout << i << " x " << j << " = " << i * j << std::endl;
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;  // print a newline after each row
}
```
And here is the equivalent code in C#:
```
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    for (int j = 1; j <= 10; j++) {
        Console.WriteLine($"{i} x {j} = {i * j}");
    }
    Console.WriteLine();  // print a newline after each row
}
```
Note that the syntax may vary slightly depending on the programming language and its version.
